s2star  aAvailable Open Access under CC-BY-NC licence. Ongoing conflicts between neoliberal and post-neoliberal politics have resulted in growing social instability in Latin America. This book explores the cultural dynamics of neoliberalism and anti-neoliberal resistance in Latin America as a complex set of interrelated cultural forms, examining the ways in which neoliberalism has transformed public discourses of self and social relationships, popular cultures and modes of everyday experience. Contributors from an international range of different disciplinary perspectives look at how Latin Americans construct subjectivities, build communities and make meaning in their everyday lives in order to analyse the discourses and cultural practices through which a societal consensus for the pursuit of neoliberal politics may be established, defended and contested.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aSocial sciences (General). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aA. Skolnick, Jenifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlvarado, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaguaceda Noriega, Armando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDel Percio, Enrique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGómez Michel, Gerardo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGómez, Gerardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJungwon, Park, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez, Magdalena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re